Student Laboratory Exercise: Wireshark 
Display Filters and Network Traffic 
Analysis 
Objective 
The purpose of this laboratory exercise is to learn and apply Wireshark display filters for 
analyzing captured network traffic. Students will generate different types of network traffic 
using Nmap and web browsing activities, capture the traffic using Wireshark, and use display 
filters to isolate and analyze specific packets and protocols. 
Learning Outcomes 
Upon successful completion of this lab, students will be able to: 
• Capture network traffic using Wireshark. 
• Generate various network scanning activities using Nmap. 
• Differentiate between capture filters and display filters. 
• Apply protocol, IP address, port-based, and packet-field display filters. 
• Analyze TCP flags, DNS traffic, and HTTP communications. 
• Investigate network scanning patterns and web traffic behavior. 
Software Requirements 
• Windows Operating System 
• Wireshark 
• Nmap 
• Metasploitable Virtual Machine 
Testbed Setup 
Step 1: Start Metasploitable 
1. Boot the Metasploitable virtual machine. 
2. Determine and record its IP address using the following command: 
ifconfig 
or 
ip addr 
3. Note the IP address for later use. 
Metasploitable IP Address: ______________________ 
Step 2: Install Required Tools 
1. Download and install Nmap on the Windows machine. 
2. Launch Wireshark. 
3. Select the active LAN/Ethernet interface. 
4. Start packet capture. 
Part A: Generate Network Traffic Using 
Nmap 
Open Command Prompt and execute the following commands, replacing 
<Metasploitable_IP> with the actual IP address of the target system. 
Host Discovery and Scanning 
nmap -A <Metasploitable_IP> 
nmap -T1 <Metasploitable_IP> 
nmap -T4 <Metasploitable_IP> 
nmap -T5 <Metasploitable_IP> 
nmap -sn 192.168.1.0/24 
TCP Scan Types 
nmap -sS <Metasploitable_IP> 
nmap -sT <Metasploitable_IP> 
Port Scanning 
nmap -p 1-1000 <Metasploitable_IP> 
nmap -sS -p- -T4 <Metasploitable_IP> 
UDP and Service Detection 
nmap -sU <Metasploitable_IP> 
nmap -sV <Metasploitable_IP> 
Operating System Detection 
nmap -O <Metasploitable_IP> 
